{"title_page": "Phyllis Hyman (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Phyllis Hyman\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Phyllis Hyman]]\n| cover      = Hyman phyllishyman1.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = April 2, 1977\n| recorded   = 1976\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Total Experience Records|Total Experience Recording Studios]]<br><small>([[Hollywood]], [[California]])</small>\n<br>[[Sigma Sound Studios]]<br><small>([[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]])</small>\n[[Record Plant]]<br><small>([[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]])</small>\n| genre      = {{flat list|\n*[[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]\n*[[soul music|soul]]\n*[[jazz]]\n*[[disco]]}}\n| length     = 44:34\n| label      = [[Buddah Records|Buddah]]\n| producer   = Larry Alexander, John Davis, [[Jerry Peters]], and Sandy Torano\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Sing a Song (album)|Sing a Song]]\n| next_year  = 1979\n}}\n{{Album ratings|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]|rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AllmusicReview\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r291078|pure_url=yes}} | title= ''Phyllis Hyman'' debut album | work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[All Media Guide]]|accessdate=2011-07-25}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Phyllis Hyman''''' is the self-titled solo debut studio [[album]] by American [[Soul music|soul]] [[singer-songwriter]] [[Phyllis Hyman]]. It was released by [[Buddah Records]] in 1977. The album charted at number 107 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/phyllis-hyman-r291078/charts-awards |title=Phyllis Hyman - Phyllis Hyman |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2012-03-05}}</ref> and of the singles released from the album, \"No One Can Love You More\" was the most successful, charting at number 58 in the ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot Soul]] singles chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/phyllis-hyman-p4535/charts-awards/billboard-singles |title=Phyllis Hyman |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2012-03-05}}</ref>\n\n==Album information==\nAfter recording a [[cover version]] of [[The Stylistics]]' 1971 hit \"[[Betcha by Golly, Wow]]\" that appeared on [[Norman Connors]]' 1976 ''You Are My Starship'' album, Hyman was signed to Buddah and began work on her debut. The album featured the hits \"Loving You - Losing You\", and \"I Don't Want to Lose You\", an R&B ballad (originally recorded by [[The Spinners (U.S. band)|The Spinners]]). ''Phyllis Hyman'' has since been re-issued on CD. This re-issue is out of print; however, eight of the tracks are available on ''The Best of Phyllis Hyman \u2013 The Buddah Years'', issued by Sequel Records in 1990.\nIn 1996 RCA records issued the CD ''Loving You, Losing You, The Classic Balladry of Phyllis Hyman'', which included a previously unreleased track from the 1977 recording session, \"Sounds Like a Love Song\".\n\n==Track listing==\nSide One:\n# \"Loving You - Losing You\" ([[Thom Bell]]) - 7:41\n# \"No One Can Love You More\" ([[Skip Scarborough]]) - 4:20\n# \"One Thing on My Mind\"  ([[Evie Sands]], Richard Germinaro) - 5:30\n# \"I Don't Want to Lose You\" (Thom Bell, [[Linda Creed]]) - 5:31\n# \"Deliver the Love\" ([[Onaje Allan Gumbs]], Ausar Sahw) 3:02\nSide Two:\n# \"Was Yesterday Such a Long Time Ago\" (M. Goode, Buddy Scott) - 4:55\n# \"Night Bird Gets the Love\" (Muhyi Shakoor, Clifford Carter) - 4:20\n# \"Beautiful Man of Mine\" (Larry Alexander) - 6:20\n# \"Children of the World\" ([[Hubert Eaves III]]) - 2:55\n\n==Personnel==\n* Larry Alexander - [[Background Vocals]]\n* Maxine Anderson - [[Background Vocals]]\n* [[Gary Bartz]]: [[Tenor saxophone]]\n* Errol \"Crusher\" Bennett - [[Percussion]]\n* Carla Benson - [[Background Vocals]]\n* Evette Benton - [[Background Vocals]]\n* [[Hiram Bullock]] - [[Guitar]]\n* Cecil Bridgewater - [[Trumpet]]\n* Charles Collins - [[Drum kit|Drums]]\n* Ann Esther Davis - [[Background Vocals]]\n* John Davis - [[Keyboard instrument|Keyboards]]\n* [[Hubert Eaves III]] - [[Piano]], Rhythm, [[Moog Synthesizer]]\n* Scott Edwards - [[Bass guitar]]\n* Michael Foreman - [[Bass guitar]]\n* Jim Gilstrap - [[Background Vocals]]\n* [[Onaje Allan Gumbs]] - [[Piano]], Rhythm, [[Keyboard instrument|Keyboards]]\n* Billy Harner - [[Background Vocals]]\n* Dennis Harris - [[Guitar]]\n* Phyllis Hyman - [[Background Vocals]]\n* [[Barbara Ingram]] - [[Background Vocals]]\n* [[Anthony Jackson (musician)|Anthony Jackson]] - [[Bass guitar]]\n* Virgil Jones - [[Trumpet]]\n* [[Steve Jordan (musician)|Steve Jordan]] - [[Drum kit|Drums]]\n* [[Will Lee (bassist)|Will Lee]] - [[Bass guitar]]\n* John Lehman - [[Background Vocals]]\n* Victor Lewis - [[Drum kit|Drums]]\n* Bill Lowe - [[Trombone]]\n* [[Reggie Lucas]] - [[Guitar]]\n* [[Harvey Mason|Harvey Mason, Sr.]] - [[Timpani]]\n* [[Andy Newmark]] - [[Drum kit|Drums]]\n* [[Jerry Peters]] - [[Keyboard instrument|Keyboards]]\n* Greg Poree - [[Guitar]]\n* Raymond Lee Pounds - [[Drum kit|Drums]]\n* Janice Robinson - [[Trombone]]\n* Richard Rome - [[Keyboard instrument|Keyboards]]\n* John Rowin - [[Guitar]]\n* [[Skip Scarborough]] - [[Keyboard instrument|Keyboards]]\n* Craig Snyder - [[Guitar]]\n* Jerry Steinholtz - [[Drum kit|Drums]]\n* Charles Sullivan - [[Trumpet]]\n* Sandy Torano - [[Guitar]] and [[Background Vocals]]\n* Larry Washington - [[Percussion]]\n* Gregory Williams - [[French Horn]]\n* Kiane Zawadi - [[Trombone]]\n\n===Production===\n* Producers: Larry Alexander, John Davis, [[Jerry Peters]], Sandy Torano\n* Arrangers: John Davis, [[Jerry Peters]], [[Onaje Allan Gumbs]]\n* Engineer: Fred Torchio\n* Production Coordination: Bernadette Fauver\n* Liner Notes: David Nathan\n* Art Direction: Milton Sincoff\n* Photography: [[Joel Brodsky]]\n* Executive Producer: [[Lewis Merenstein]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{discogs master|141190|Phyllis Hyman}}\n\n{{Phyllis Hyman}}\n[[Category:1977 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Buddah Records albums]]\n[[Category:Phyllis Hyman albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jerry Peters]]\n[[Category:Albums with cover art by Joel Brodsky]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Phyllis Hyman\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Phyllis Hyman]]\n| cover      = Hyman phyllishyman1.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = April 2, 1977\n| recorded   = 1976\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Total Experience Records|Total Experience Recording Studios]]<br><small>([[Hollywood]], [[California]])</small>\n<br>[[Sigma Sound Studios]]<br><small>([[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]])</small>\n[[Record Plant]]<br><small>([[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]])</small>\n| genre      = {{flat list|\n*[[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]\n*[[soul music|soul]]\n*[[jazz]]\n*[[disco]]}}\n| length     = 44:34\n| label      = [[Buddah Records|Buddah]]\n| producer   = Larry Alexander, John Davis, [[Jerry Peters]], and Sandy Torano\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Sing a Song (album)|Sing a Song]]\n| next_year  = 1979\n}}\n{{Album ratings|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]|rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AllmusicReview\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r291078|pure_url=yes}} | title= ''Phyllis Hyman'' debut album | work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[All Media Guide]]|accessdate=2011-07-25}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Phyllis Hyman''''' is the self-titled solo debut studio [[album]] by American [[Soul music|soul]] [[singer-songwriter]] [[Phyllis Hyman]]. It was released by [[Buddah Records]] in 1977. The album charted at #107 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart,  \n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/phyllis-hyman-r291078/charts-awards |title=Phyllis Hyman - Phyllis Hyman |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2012-03-05}}</ref> of the singles released from the album: \"No One Can Love You More\" was the most successful, charting at #58 in the ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot Soul]] singles chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist